Reasoning: The paper deals with optimization algorithms for nonconvex problems, which is a common topic in machine learning and optimization. The use of stochastic gradient algorithms and the focus on finding second-order stationary points suggest that the paper belongs to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The analysis of the algorithm's complexity and convergence properties suggests that it could also belong to the sub-categories of cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of perturbations and the focus on escaping saddle points suggest that the paper could also belong to the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the extension of the results to online problems suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory).
